  <summary>Yuri Orlov is a globetrotting arms dealer and, through some of the deadliest war zones, he struggles to stay one step ahead of a relentless Interpol agent, his business rivals and even some of his customers who include many of the world's most notorious dictators. Finally, he must also face his own conscience.</summary>
  <reviews>
    <item index="0">
      <text>Niccol is no stranger to hot-button issues, but he outdoes his previous efforts by injecting this satire of war profiteering in the Halliburton age with a wicked arsenic wit.</text>
      <source>Time Out</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.fresh</image>
      <link>http://www.timeout.com/film/newyork/reviews/83020/lord_of_war.html</link>
      <author>Dave Calhoun</author>
    </item>
    <item index="1">
      <text>Even though Niccol sometimes puts unnecessary homilies in the mouths of his characters, he mostly pulls off the tricky feat of being direct and breezy at the same time. "Lord of War" skims along like a dance routine.</text>
      <source>Salon.com</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.fresh</image>
      <link>http://www.salon.com/2005/09/16/lord_of_war/</link>
      <author>Stephanie Zacharek</author>
    </item>
    <item index="2">
      <text>A caustic satire masquerading as an action adventure.</text>
      <source>Chicago Reader</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.fresh</image>
      <link>http://www.chicagoreader.com/movies/archives/2005/0905/050916.html</link>
      <author>Jonathan Rosenbaum</author>
    </item>
    <item index="3">
      <text>There are the makings here of a really good feature or an even better documentary, but as it stands, Lord of War is not quite either.</text>
      <source>San Francisco Chronicle</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.rotten</image>
      <link>http://sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2005/09/16/DDGKGENKUH1.DTL&amp;type=movies</link>
      <author>Mick LaSalle</author>
    </item>
    <item index="4">
      <text>Lord of War tosses grenades and then fearfully runs from them.</text>
      <source>Toronto Star</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.rotten</image>
      <link>http://WWW.TheStar.COM/NASApp/cs/ContentServer?pagename=thestar/Layout/Article_Type1&amp;c=Article&amp;cid=1126864957758&amp;call_pageid=1022183557980&amp;col=1022183560753</link>
      <author>Peter Howell</author>
    </item>
    <item index="5">
      <text>Lord of War has a hip, gonzo energy to it and it's often transfixing to watch and listen to. But it's finally just as empty as the man it's about.</text>
      <source>Washington Post</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.rotten</image>
      <link>http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/09/15/AR2005091502423.html</link>
      <author>Ann Hornaday</author>
    </item>
    <item index="6">
      <text>His heavy-handedness and inability to humanize and explain his hero mean that even the choir Niccol is preaching to won't be moved by Lord of War.</text>
      <source>Orlando Sentinel</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.rotten</image>
      <link>http://www.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment/movies/orl-lordwar05sep16,0,6590797.story?coll=orl-calmoviestop</link>
      <author>Roger Moore</author>
    </item>
    <item index="7">
      <text>Its best moments burn with irony.</text>
      <source>Houston Chronicle</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.fresh</image>
      <link>http://www.chron.com/cs/CDA/moviestory.mpl/ae/movies/reviews/3355829</link>
      <author>Amy Biancolli</author>
    </item>
    <item index="8">
      <text>It's just a well-intended essay, a movie when necessary but not necessarily a movie.</text>
      <source>Globe and Mail</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.rotten</image>
      <link>http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20050916.wxlord16/BNStory/Entertainment/</link>
      <author>Rick Groen</author>
    </item>
